#Text=Melbourne/St Kilda
#Text=St
#Text=Kilda
#Text=is a vibrant beachside suburb of Port Phillip , in south-eastern inner Melbourne , Australia .
#Text=St. Kilda is famous for its beach life and the bar and restaurant scene along Fitzroy Street .
#Text=Formally known to be seedy and run down , there has been a revival in the 21st century as young professionals and travellers have increased in numbers .
#Text=Get in
#Text=St Kilda can be reached from the City Centre by public transport ; a map of St Kilda and the surrounding area 's public transport network is available on the PTV website .
#Text=By tram
#Text=The best way to reach St Kilda from the city centre is by tram .
#Text=The journey takes approximately 25 minutes .
#Text=Route 96

#Text=from along Bourke Street or Southern Cross Station ( towards St Kilda Beach ) - the fastest of the three , it functions as a light rail travelling along the former railway , taking about 20 minutes with a 6-10 minute frequency .
#Text=It operates exclusively with high-capacity , low-floor trams but can be very crowded .
#Text=Within St Kilda , it travels along Fitzroy Street , the Esplanade and terminates at Acland Street .
#Text=Route 16
#Text=( also 3a on weekends ) from along Swanston Street or Flinders Street Station ( towards Kew ) - passes along Fitzroy Street , the Esplanade and Carlisle Street .
#Text=It then travels into the neighbouring suburbs of Balaclava and St Kilda East , before heading onwards to Kew in Boroondara .
#Text=Route 12
#Text=from along Collins Street ( towards St Kilda ) - passes through the residential streets of the inner south and St Kilda West before terminating at Fitzroy Street .
#Text=The eastern periphery of St Kilda , including St Kilda East , can be reached by Route 67 ( towards Carnegie ) , or by Route 3 or Route 3A ( towards East Malvern ) .
#Text=By train
#Text=St Kilda does not have a railway station , with the former railway converted to the Route 96 light rail tram .
#Text=St Kilda East is served by Balaclava Station on the Sandringham Line .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Buses are useful for accessing the more residential areas of St Kilda and its surrounds that lack tram services .
#Text=High-frequency Route 246 operates along Punt Road and connects St Kilda East to Melbourne 's inner east .
#Text=Bus routes 600 , 606 , 922 and 923 run via Mitford St and Broadway in Elwood , south of St Kilda .
#Text=By bike
#Text=Melbourne 's Blue Bike docked bike scheme extends down as far as St Kilda - and the ride between here and the city centre is very pleasant cycling .
#Text=Of course , Obikes ( dockless ) are ubiquitous if you care to pick one up and go for a ride along the beach .
#Text=By car
#Text=From the City Centre , St Kilda is best reached via St Kilda Road , the continuation of Swanston Street in the CBD .
#Text=At St Kilda Junction , follow the signage for Fitzroy St.
#Text=The journey takes approximately 25 minutes , depending on traffic .
#Text=See
#Text=Jewish Museum of Australia
#Text=, 26 Alma Rd ( Trams 3 or 67 : Stop 32 , Alma Rd and walk east along Alma Rd ) , ☏ +61385343600 , ✉ info@jewishmuseum.com.au .
#Text=Tu - Th 10AM — 4PM , Su 10AM — 5PM .
#Text=An engaging museum that depicts the story of the Jewish community in Melbourne and Australia , in addition to the history of the strong local congregation within St Kilda and Caulfield .
#Text=Houses a number of artefacts from around the world .
#Text=Guided tours available on request .
#Text=Adult $ 10 , child/concession $ 5 .
#Text=St Kilda Beach
#Text=, 43 Jacka Blvd ( Trams 3a , 16 or 96 : Stop 136 , The Esplanade ) .
#Text=One of Melbourne 's most famous and popular beaches , it is an enjoyable place to spend an afternoon .
#Text=Apart from the omnipresent swimming , popular activities include sunbathing , sailing , beach volleyball , sandcastle-building , jetskiing and kitesurfing .
#Text=The beach is regularly patrolled in the Summer by surf lifesavers .
#Text=St Kilda Botanical Gardens

#Text=, Cnr Herbert & Blessington St ( Tram 96 : Stop 140 , Barkly St terminus and walk along Blessington St ; or tram 67 : Stop 36 , St Kilda Primary School and walk along Mozart St ) , ☏ +61392096777 , ✉ ospace@portphillip.vic.gov.au .
#Text=Gardens : sunrise – sunset , conservatory : M – F 10:30AM – 3:30PM , Sa Su sunrise – sunset .
#Text=St Kilda 's own botanical gardens were established in the 1800s and are an oasis of tranquility amongst the area 's bustling surrounds .

#Text=A short five minute walk down a side street from St Kilda 's main hub , its features include a large conservatory , glasshouses , a gazebo , playground , a giant chess board and an ornamental lake .
#Text=Detailed information about the plants and wildlife are available on the council 's website .
#Text=St Kilda Pier , Breakwater and Kiosk
#Text=( Home of St Kilda 's Little Penguin colony ) , Pier Rd ( Trams 3a , 16 or 96 : Stop 135 , Jacka Blvd ) , ☏ +61131963 , ✉ info@parks.vic.gov.au .
#Text=The long , wooden pier is a popular spot for walking and fishing .
#Text=Many of the fishermen along the pier will be happy to show you their catch if politely asked .
#Text=At the end of the pier sits the historic kiosk , now a restaurant , which was rebuilt to the original plans in 2006 after an earlier arson attack .
#Text=At the far end of the pier is the St Kilda breakwater , which is home to native water rats and the popular little penguins .
#Text=The colony has existed since the 1950s , nestled amongst the rocks of the breakwater .
#Text=As it 's not an official tourist development , you can see the penguins for free most days at sunset in the publicly accessible area of the breakwater .
#Text=Respect the penguins by not touching them , feeding them or using flash photography .
#Text=Alternatively , boat tours are available through Parks Victoria via their website .
#Text=Do
#Text=Luna Park
#Text=, 18 Lower Esplanade ( Trams 3a , 16 or 96 : Stop 138 , Luna Park ) , ☏ +61395255033 , ✉ justforfun@lunapark.com.au .
#Text=Opening hours vary , although generally open 11AM-6PM weekends and 11AM-8PM weekdays during school holidays ; closed weekdays during school term .
#Text=This St Kilda icon 's famous mouth entrance continues to grace Melbourne 's postcards and for good reason .
#Text=Built in 1912 , the historic amusement park is free to enter , with a number of rides to keep the young and young at heart entertained .
#Text=The fabled Scenic Railway is the oldest continually operating wooden-framed rollercoaster in the world , and gives panoramic views over the nearby bay .
#Text=Other rides include all the usual favourites , such as a Ferris wheel , dodgem cars and a ghost train .
#Text=A great day out for kids and families .
#Text=In poor weather , some rides may close , including the historic rollercoaster .
#Text=Single ride : adult ( 13+ ) $ 11 , child ( 4-12 ) $ 9 , infant $ 5 ; unlimited ticket : adult $ 49.50 , child $ 39.50 , infant $ 16.50 .
#Text=St Kilda Sea Baths
#Text=, 10/18 Jacka Blvd ( Trams 3a , 16 and 96 : Stop 136 , The Esplanade ) .

#Text=An old Melbourne institution perched on the St Kilda foreshore , the Sea Baths building now has a variety of different functions , including a gymnasium , a spa , a sea water pool and countless restaurants , bars and cafés .
